{{update|date=December 2010}} {{Infobox Organization |name = Pacific Maritime Association |image = |image_border = |size = <!-- default 200 --> |alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> |caption = |abbreviation = PMA |motto = |formation = <!-- {{Start date and years ago|1921|9|15}} --> |extinction = <!-- date of extinction, optional --> |type = <!-- GO, NGO, IGO, INGO, etc --> |status = Trade Association <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc --> |purpose = <!-- focus as e.g. humanitarian, peacekeeping, etc --> |headquarters = [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], [[California]]<ref>[http://www.pmanet.org/office-locations Pacific Maritime Association: Locations]</ref> |location = |coords = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template --> |region_served = [[West Coast of the United States|Pacific Coast]] |membership = |language = <!-- official languages --> |leader_title = President & CEO<!-- position title for the leader of the org --> |leader_name = James C. McKenna<ref>[http://www.pmanet.org/pma-leadership Pacific Maritime Association: Leadership]</ref> |main_organ = Board of Directors <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc --> |parent_organization = <!-- if one --> |affiliations = <!-- if any --> |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = [http://www.pmanet.org pmanet.org] |remarks = }} The '''Pacific Maritime Association''' ('''PMA''') is a non-profit organization based in [[San Francisco, California]] that represents employers of the shipping industry on the [[West Coast of the United States|Pacific coast]].<ref name="ftrobertwright">Robert Wright. "US supply chains face lengthy turmoil despite port deals". ''Financial Times'', February 23, 2015, p. 8.</ref>
==Background== The Pacific Maritime Association was founded in 1949<ref name="pmaoverview">[http://www.pmanet.org/overview Pacific Maritime Association: Overview]</ref> as a non-profit corporation. Its principal business is to negotiate and administer labor agreements with the [[International Longshore and Warehouse Union]] (ILWU). PMA’s 72 members are cargo carriers, terminal operators, and stevedores that operate along the U.S. West Coast.
In 1960, it negotiated the [[Mechanization and Modernization Agreement 1960|Mechanization and Modernization Agreement]].<ref name="pmaoverview"/>
As of December 2012, PMA members employed nearly 14,000 registered longshore, clerk and foreman workers at 29 west coast ports in California, Oregon, and Washington, and thousands more “casual” workers, who typically work part-time. Since the 2002 agreement that brought the widespread use of technology to the West Coast, the registered workforce has increased by 32 percent.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}
In 2015, it negotiated a five-year contract with the ILWU.<ref name="ftrobertwright"/>
