{{Infobox software | name = Priority Matrix | title = | logo = | screenshot = Priority_Matri_for_iPad.png | caption = Screenshot of Priority Matrix for [[iPad]] | collapsible = | author = | developer = Appfluence LLC | released = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} --> | discontinued = | latest release version = 2.2.20150401 | latest release date = {{Start date and age|2015|04|01}} | latest preview version = | latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | programming language = | operating system = [[Windows]], [[macOS]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] | platform = | size = | language = | alexa = 77,058 ({{As of|2014|11|alt=December 2014}})<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/appfluence.com |title=Alexa appfluence.com traffic results |publisher=[[Alexa Internet|Alexa]] |accessdate=November 10, 2014}}</ref> | genre = [[Time management]] software | license = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]] | website = {{URL|appfluence.com}} }}
'''Priority Matrix''' is a [[time management]] software application that is supported on a number of platforms, including [[Microsoft Windows]], [[macOS|Mac OS X]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], and [[iOS]]. It is based on the [[Eisenhower method|Eisenhower Method]] of arranging tasks by urgency and importance in a 2x2 [[matrix (mathematics)|matrix]]. Priority Matrix offers a [[Cloud computing|cloud]]-based synchronization of data, allowing for data management across multiple devices. The application is also loosely based on [[David Allen (author)|David Allen]]'s [[Getting Things Done]] methodology of improving productivity.
==Features== * '''Quadrants-based task prioritization'''- The 2x2 time management matrix, based on the Eisenhower Method of time management, is the general framework on which Priority Matrix is run. The quadrants organize tasks based on importance and urgency.<ref>{{cite web|title=Time Management for Sales People|url=http://salestrong.co.uk/time-management-for-sales-people/|publisher=www.salestrong.co.uk|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> In Priority Matrix, the four quadrants' default labels are: Critical and Immediate, Critical but not Immediate, Not Critical but Immediate, and Uncategorized. * '''Task [[drag and drop]]'''- Tasks and projects are capable of being dragged from one location to another, allowing users to change a task's priority level without having to create a new item altogether. * '''Project import/export'''- Entire projects can be exported into the program's native file format, .pmatrix, for transferring a workspace quickly. * '''Cloud-based synchronization across platforms'''- Despite running on several different platforms, Priority Matrix is able to sync project and task data over the cloud, with data being stored on Priority Matrix's [[Server (computing)|server]]s. * '''Progress and date tracking'''- Dates and deadlines can be made for each task, providing notifications and allowing users to track their progress over time. * '''Project summary emails and reporting'''- Emails can be created out of entire projects, for quick reporting and sending a summary of projects. * '''Color and label customization'''- Each quadrant's background can be changed to any color in the [[RGB]] [[spectrum]]. For further customization, every task has icons that can be selected to represent a specific task. * '''Template system'''- New projects can be created from sample templates, to avoid repetitive data input. Various templates are available <ref>{{cite web|title=Priority Matrix templates|url=https://sync.appfluence.com/templates/Innovation-Management-Matrix/|publisher=appfluence.com|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> for different thought processes.
==Reception== Across the various platforms, Priority Matrix has over 90,000 paid customers,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.appfluence.com/ |title=Appfluence - Plan differently. - The best desktop to do list app for Windows, Mac, iPhone and iPad |publisher=Appfluence |accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref> and has been ranked among the 10 highest downloaded [[productivity]] [[Mobile app|apps]] in the [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.appfluence.com/productivity/priority-matrix-top-10-free-productivity-iphone-app/ |title=productivity 151: striving for continuous improvement - a blog by appfluence |publisher=Appfluence |accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref> [[PC Magazine]] has ranked the [[iPad]] version of Priority Matrix among its 100 Best iPad Apps in 2011, 2012, and 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/slideshow_viewer/0,3253,l%253D250054%2526a%253D250058%2526po%253D24,00.asp?p=n |title=The 100 Best iPad Apps - Priority Matrix - Slideshow from PCMag.com |publisher=PC Magazine |accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref> In addition, the product has garnered a 4 out of 5-star rating or better on the Apple App Store on both the [[iPhone]] and iPad platforms, with over 1,300 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/priority-matrix/id364906005?mt=8 |title= Priority Matrix for iPad |publisher=Apple Inc. |accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref> An [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version was added to the [[Google Play|Play Store]] September 2013. As of 2014, this version had an average rating of 3.9, with 1,000-5,000 installs.{{cn|date=January 2016}}
